{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493261"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:03:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1271"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1271"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.25,0.02,0.68,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1271"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1231"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to her GP with constipation, weight gain and fatigue over the last two months. Her medical history includes hypertension (perindopril), atrial fibrillation (digoxin, amiodarone and rivaroxaban) and asthma (salbutamol). She has a 20 pack-year history and states that she consumes four glasses of wine per evening on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her BMI is 30 and her pulse is 58/min. ECG demonstrates atrial fibrillation. Blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 98g/L [115-155]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 100fl [80-98]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver function tests: normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes, urea and creatinine: normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone 12 mIU/L [0.5-4]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFree T4 8 pmol/L [10-25]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-thyroid peroxidase antibody: high\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolate 10 nmol/L [6.5-45]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin B12 600pmol/L [\u0026gt;260]\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide alcohol cessation counselling","Cease amiodarone","Increase dose of amiodarone","Prescribe thyroid hormone replacement","Prescribe iron tablets"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical symptoms are consistent with hypothyroidism, which is supported by obesity and bradycardia on examination. This diagnosis is confirmed with a raised TSH level with low T4, suggesting likely primary hypothyroidism. The level of anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies (anti-TPO) suggests a high likelihood of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis. Primary hypothyroidism is treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid hormone replacement\u003C/strong\u003E (levothyroxine).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypothyroid disease is the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s macrocytic anaemia. Although this patient has a high alcohol intake (which may also cause macrocytic anaemia) her \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol use\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be contributing to her persistent symptoms of weight gain, constipation and fatigue. Perhaps it is an assumption to state that the patient has a high alcohol intake - she admits to four glasses a night at the weekend (Fri, Sat, Sun), but it is well known that patients tend to understate their alcohol consumption - particularly when asked about the subject by a doctor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn uncommon side effect of amiodarone is hypothyroidism. However, this is less likely given the elevated anti-TPO. As such, there is no indication to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecease her amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the dose\u003C/strong\u003E would also be inappropriate.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EWhile she has anaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003Eiron supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be effective given it is likely related to her hypothyroidism (iron deficiency anaemia is usually microcytic).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Increased levels of anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies suggests a diagnosis of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis"],"references":["So M, MacIsaac R, Grossmann M. Hypothyroidism: Investigation and Management. Australian Family Physician. 2012;41(8):556-562. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/hypothyroidism/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1271"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-17T11:32:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T14:17:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"